2.3 Quantum Processing Subsystem

2.3.1 Heterogeneous Qubit Architecture

QUENNE employs multiple qubit technologies, each optimized for specific functions:

Superconducting Qubits (Main Compute):

· Role: High-speed gate operations
· Specifications: 99.9% 2Q fidelity, 50ns gate times, 6-way connectivity
· Innovation: Tunable couplers for dynamic connectivity graphs
· Scale: 128,000 PQ per Tier 0 hub

Trapped Ion Qubits (Memory/Storage):

· Role: Long-coherence storage, high-fidelity operations
· Specifications: T₂ > 10 seconds, 99.99% 2Q fidelity, 200μs gate times
· Innovation: Photonic interconnects between ion chains
· Scale: 32,000 PQ per Tier 0 hub

Photonic Qubits (Interconnect):

· Role: Quantum state transfer, entanglement distribution
· Specifications: Telecom wavelength (1550nm), 10dB loss tolerance
· Innovation: All-photonic quantum repeaters
· Scale: 32,000 PQ equivalent per Tier 0 hub

2.3.2 Quantum Error Correction Implementation

```
Surface Code Architecture:
- Code Distance: d=31 (Tier 0), d=15 (Tier 1), d=7 (Tier 2)
- Physical-to-Logical Ratio: ~2d² (≈2000:1 for d=31)
- Logical Error Rate: <10⁻¹⁵ per operation
- Decoding Latency: <100ns using custom ASICs
- Innovation: Neural network-accelerated decoding with FPGA implementation
```

2.3.3 Quantum-Classical Interface

· Control Electronics: Cryogenic CMOS at 4K (reducing thermal noise)
· Timing System: Sub-nanosecond synchronization across 1000+ control channels
· Calibration: Machine learning-optimized, continuous recalibration
· Data Conversion: Quantum state tomography with compressive sensing

2.4 Neuromorphic Processing Subsystem

2.4.1 NeuroChip Architecture

```
NeuroChip X9 Specifications:
- Process: 5nm CMOS with embedded RRAM
- Density: 268 million neurons, 274 billion synapses per chip
- Energy Efficiency: 5 pJ per spike (including synaptic operations)
- Learning: On-chip STDP with configurable learning rules
- Connectivity: Sparse, event-driven communication

Key Innovations:
1. Analog-Digital Hybrid Design:
   - Membrane potentials: Analog computation
   - Spike generation: Digital thresholding
   - Synaptic weights: Analog storage (RRAM)

2. Structural Plasticity:
   - Dynamic synapse creation/pruning
   - Homeostatic regulation
   - Neuromodulation pathways

3. 3D Integration:
   - Base die: Neuron/synapse arrays
   - Memory die: HBM3 for weight storage
   - Interposer: Optical I/O for chip-to-chip communication
```

2.4.2 System Integration

· NeuroRack 9000: 256 NeuroChips, 68B neurons, 70T synapses
· Interconnect: Optical AER (Address-Event Representation) fabric
· Power: 4kW per rack, liquid cooling with 40°C inlet temperature
· Scalability: Linear scaling to 1000+ racks with 3D torus topology

2.5 6G Network Fabric

2.5.1 Physical Layer Innovations

```
Frequency Bands:
- Sub-6 GHz: 3.5-7 GHz for coverage and mobility
- mmWave: 24-47 GHz for capacity and low latency
- THz: 100-300 GHz for extreme throughput (1 Tbps peak)
- D-Band: 130-175 GHz for backhaul and fixed wireless

Antenna Systems:
- Massive MIMO: 256×256 elements with holographic beamforming
- Reconfigurable Intelligent Surfaces: 1024-element programmable metasurfaces
- Quantum-Enhanced Receivers: Rydberg atom sensors for ultra-sensitive detection

Performance Targets:
- Peak Rate: 1 Tbps downlink, 500 Gbps uplink
- Latency: 0.1 ms air interface, <1 ms end-to-end
- Reliability: 99.99999% for control channels
- Density: 10⁷ devices/km²
```

2.5.2 Network Architecture

```
Protocol Stack Innovations:
1. PHY Layer: OTFS (Orthogonal Time Frequency Space) modulation
2. MAC Layer: Grant-free access with quantum-inspired scheduling
3. Network Layer: Integrated quantum internet protocol (QIP)
4. Transport Layer: Quantum-safe encryption with forward secrecy
5. Application Layer: Quantum computing as a native service

Network Slicing for QUENNE:
- Slice 1 (Quantum Control): <100μs latency, 99.9999999% reliability
- Slice 2 (Neuromorphic Spike Traffic): Burst-tolerant, multicast-optimized
- Slice 3 (Quantum Data): Loss-intolerant, entanglement-aware routing
- Slice 4 (Classical Data): High-throughput, best-effort delivery
```

2.5.3 Quantum Network Integration

· Entanglement Distribution: Heralded entanglement generation at 1 kHz over 100 km
· Quantum Memory Nodes: Atomic ensembles with 1-second coherence
· Quantum Repeaters: All-photonic design with no quantum memory requirement
· Management: Software-defined quantum networking

2.6 Hybrid Orchestration System

2.6.1 QuantumOS: The Unified Operating System

```
Microkernel Architecture:
- Size: 100K lines of formally verified code (seL4 heritage)
- Real-time guarantees: Deterministic scheduling with µs precision
- Security: Capability-based access control for quantum resources
- Virtualization: Lightweight containers for algorithm isolation

Key Services:
1. Qubit Resource Manager: Allocation, calibration, retirement
2. Entanglement Service: Bell pair generation, distillation, routing
3. Error Correction Scheduler: Surface code cycle coordination
4. Neuromorphic Network Manager: Spike routing, plasticity control
5. 6G Slice Orchestrator: End-to-end network slice management
```

2.6.2 Compiler and Toolchain

```
Unified Programming Model:
Frontend: Domain-specific languages (Q#, NeuroPy, classical)
│
├── Quantum Compiler (QIR-based)
│   ├── Architecture-aware mapping
│   ├── Error-adaptive optimization
│   └── Pulse-level code generation
│
├── Neuromorphic Compiler (SNN-focused)
│   ├── ANN-to-SNN conversion
│   ├── Energy-aware mapping
│   └── Structural optimization
│
└── Hybrid Partitioning Compiler
    ├── Profiling across quantum, neuromorphic, classical
    ├── Cost-model-based partitioning
    └── Glue code generation

Optimization Targets:
- Energy minimization (pJ per operation)
- Latency constraints (application-dependent)
- Fidelity requirements (quantum and neuromorphic)
- Resource utilization (maximize throughput)
```

2.6.3 Runtime System

· Dynamic Re-partitioning: Based on system load and qubit quality
· Fault Tolerance: Automatic failover between computational modes
· Energy Management: Dynamic voltage/frequency scaling with workload
· Multi-tenancy: Secure isolation between users and applications

